# API & data-layer patterns

## Route Handler = orchestration only (`app/api/**/route.ts`)
Wrap with `withApiRoute` (auth/admin XOR, rate-limit, request-id, central error map).
Handler gets non-null `{ user, org, requestId }`. Parse input with Zod, call ONE service, return.
```ts
const schema = z.object({ noResi: z.string().trim().min(1).max(64) });
export const GET = withApiRoute(async (request, { org }) => {
  const parsed = schema.safeParse({ noResi: new URL(request.url).searchParams.get('noResi') ?? '' });
  if (!parsed.success) return apiValidationError(parsed.error);
  return apiSuccess(await recordingServerService.findRecentDuplicateResi(org.id, parsed.data.noResi));
}, { requireAuth: true });
```
NO business logic, NO Prisma, NO manual auth in the handler.

## Organization scope + RBAC (the data boundary)
Data is scoped by **`organizationId`**, never by user. `withApiRoute` re-resolves the caller's
membership from the DB **every request** (`resolveOrgContext`; a removed member 401s immediately,
not at JWT expiry) and hands the handler `org: { id, role }`. Pass **`org.id`** as the scope arg
to services; pass **`user.id`** ONLY as the actor (who did it) for rows that record it.
- Services take `organizationId` first; writers take `actorUserId` too and persist BOTH
  (`userId` is now actor/creator semantics, NOT scope). Per-org code sequences (S/PO/OP/RF) count
  `where: { organizationId }` inside a tx wrapped in `retryOnCodeCollision` (the `[organizationId,
code]` unique index guards the race).
- Gate elevated routes with **`requirePermission: '<key>'`** (the per-org configurable catalog of
  10 keys; OWNER bypasses, ADMIN/STAFF checked against `org.permissions`). Two tiers: VIEW keys
  (`reports.view`, `purchasing.view`, `marketplace.view`) gate a whole section's GET routes + pages
  + nav; ACTION keys (refund/void, PO cancel, catalog delete, adjust/dispose, opname post,
  marketplace manage, team manage) gate one mutation. Reserve **`minOrgRole: 'OWNER'`** for
  owner-only routes (member role-change/remove, the matrix editor, **store rename** `PATCH /org`).
  Pages use `requireOrgPermission(key)` / `requireOrgRole(min)`; `requirePlatformAdmin()` guards the
  admin-ops console (a platform `UserRole.ADMIN` is confined to `/admin` — the `authorized` callback
  + `(dashboard)` layout bounce them out of the shop). Server is the boundary; client hiding
  (`useHasPermission`, nav `permission`) is cosmetic. Catalog + pure `resolvePermissions` live in
  `modules/users/permissions/`; new orgs come only from `/api/v1/admin/organizations` and
  registration is invite-only.
- **Deliberate exceptions (stay user-scoped)**: scanner-pairing (device artifact), upload/recording
  rate-limit keys, `AuditLog`/`PairingSession.organizationId` are nullable. R2 keys are
  `${organizationId}/...` (backfilled org id == old user id, so old keys stay valid).
- Audit sensitive actions best-effort AFTER the tx via `auditService.log({ organizationId,
actorUserId, action, resource, resourceId?, metadata? })` — never throws, never inside the tx.

## Layering
- **Service** (`*.service.ts`): business logic, HTTP-free; server svc start `import 'server-only'`;
  throw module errors extending `DomainError(code, message, statusCode, details?)`.
- **Data layer**: Prisma lives in a `repository` (`*.repository.ts`) WHERE ONE EXISTS — today only
  `scanner-pairing` (e.g. `pairingRepository.findSessionUser`); every other module touches `prisma`
  directly in its server service. Prisma is NEVER in a Route Handler or UI — only the data layer.
- **Validators**: Zod schema is the single input source; export `z.infer` types.

## Errors
`handleApiError` maps ANY `DomainError` generically from code+statusCode (no module imports).
Client `apiFetch` → `ApiResult<T>` (unwraps the `{ data }` envelope; a legitimately-null
`data` STAYS null — never fall back to the whole payload, or a `null` result reads as truthy);
`apiFetchOrThrow` throws `DomainError` **preserving the real server code** — never collapse
to `UNKNOWN`.

## Session expiry (401 = global redirect)
A `401` from ANY route means the session is gone (the API only 401s via `apiUnauthorized`).
`apiFetch` broadcasts `onUnauthorized` (a listener registry in `lib/api/fetch-client.ts`);
`SessionExpiryWatcher` (mounted in `Providers`) hard-redirects to
`/login?callbackUrl=<current url>` so re-login returns the user where they were. Don't add
ad-hoc per-call 401 redirects — reuse this. (Unauthenticated route gating + the same
`callbackUrl` round-trip is already handled by `middleware.ts` + `authConfig.authorized`.)

## Data fetching (hooks)
`apiFetch`/`apiFetchOrThrow` + TanStack Query. Keys in `*-keys.ts` (one hierarchy).
Mutations invalidate the right key (`recordingKeys.active`, `.all`, `storageQueryKeys.quota`).

## Logging
`appLogger`/`logger` from `@falka/logger`: `('event.name', { ctx })`. No `console.log`,
no secrets (errors via `sanitizeError`).

## R2 presigned upload
client → `POST /uploads/presign` → `uploadService.createPresignedUpload` (quota →
`storageService.generateUploadUrl`, R2 signs content-type ONLY) → browser `PUT`s to R2 →
`POST /recordings` saves metadata. Server never proxies bytes.
